about for the last 20 minutes,
which is getting people

00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:59.690
to eat hamburgers
and bad Mexican food,

00:11:59.690 --> 00:12:01.360
which I spent a lot
of my career doing.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:08.380
What we talked about
before is, most of the time

00:12:08.380 --> 00:12:11.540
I'm not the dumbest
person in the room.

00:12:11.540 --> 00:12:13.590
Sometimes, a lot
of the times, I'm

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:16.080
not the smartest
person in the room.

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:18.420
But I do know when
lunchtime comes around,

00:12:18.420 --> 00:12:22.200
I like to choose what
I want to choose.

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:26.620
I don't particularly feel like
the smartest person in the room

00:12:26.620 --> 00:12:32.260
should be choosing what they
think I should eat for lunch.

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:35.010
I think what I said when
we were talking beforehand

00:12:35.010 --> 00:12:44.050
is, I understand why society
has laws that protect people

00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:48.890
from products that are
dangerous to society

00:12:48.890 --> 00:12:51.290
under the best of circumstances.

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:57.300
But I don't particularly think
we need laws or regulations

00:12:57.300 --> 00:13:05.880
that protect individuals
from risky products,

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:10.370
products that are risky under
the worst circumstances.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:14.390
I think that's what being an
individual is about evaluating.

00:13:14.390 --> 00:13:18.020
So I don't think it's
about lying or deceiving.

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:22.900
I think it's the difference
between products or things

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:25.920
that are always
dangerous to everybody

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:31.251
versus things that can sometimes
be dangerous to individuals.

00:13:31.251 --> 00:13:33.500
I think those things have
to be looked at differently.

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:34.970
Does that answer the question?

00:13:34.970 --> 00:13:35.640
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
I think it does.

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:36.140
OK.

00:13:36.140 --> 00:13:36.684
Very good.

00:13:36.684 --> 00:13:39.100
Just one or two more questions
about advertising before we

00:13:39.100 --> 00:13:39.933
talk about the show.

00:13:39.933 --> 00:13:41.196
What are emthymemes?

00:13:41.196 --> 00:13:42.070
That was interesting.

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:45.106
And how does it work with
our dopamine, our adrenaline?

00:13:45.106 --> 00:13:46.730
I'd be curious to
hear more about that.

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:49.063
JOSH WELTMAN: There's a section
in the book where I talk

00:13:49.063 --> 00:13:50.500
about a thing called enthymeme.

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:56.460
And an enthymene is a thing
that Aristotle refers to

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:57.760
in a book called "Rhetoric."

00:13:57.760 --> 00:14:01.500
And it's basically--
the translation

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:03.960
is "within the mind."

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:08.540
And when I was about 25,
I was reading this book

00:14:08.540 --> 00:14:10.670
while taking my first
class in advertising

00:14:10.670 --> 00:14:15.740
and learning how to come up with
concepts that were intriguing

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:17.100
and arresting to people.

00:14:17.100 --> 00:14:21.820
And I came across
this line that said,

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:24.770
when using this enthymeme
technique to try and engage

00:14:24.770 --> 00:14:26.320
somebody, here's how it works.

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:28.840
The first part of
the phrase confuses--

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:31.740
if the first part of the phrase
confuses, the second part

00:14:31.740 --> 00:14:32.580
explains.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:35.210
If the first part explains,
the second part confuses.

00:14:35.210 --> 00:14:39.050
And this discord, people
trying to figure this out,

00:14:39.050 --> 00:14:44.300
is what engages their mind
in a speaker's argument.

00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:46.760
And the example
I use in the book

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:50.700
is that Samuel Johnson
could have said,

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:54.700
there are a lot of things
to do or see in London.

00:14:54.700 --> 00:14:58.340
But what he said was, when
a man is tired of London,

00:14:58.340 --> 00:15:00.260
he's tired of life.

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:03.860
And the first part sort of
confuses, and the second part

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:04.890
explains.

00:15:04.890 --> 00:15:08.620
And you're engaged as you
go through the beginning

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:10.420
of this thing to the
end of the thing.

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:13.270
And I think that modern
advertising sort of

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:17.040
started in the mid
'60s when someone

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:21.100
discovered that if
the picture confuses,

00:15:21.100 --> 00:15:22.860
the headline explains.

00:15:22.860 --> 00:15:25.600
And if the headline confuses,
the picture explains.

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:28.960
And using images and words
together in this fashion

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:32.870
is sort of a modern
enthymeme to engage people

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:39.340
in an image that was used
to stop them from flipping

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:42.580
through a magazine, get them
interested in a television

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:46.260
commercial, make them stare
at a poster on the street.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:49.550
But this technique has been
being used for the last 40

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:51.259
years to engage people's heads.

00:15:51.259 --> 00:15:52.550
MALE SPEAKER: It's interesting.

00:15:52.550 --> 00:15:54.630
We were talking about
the way Aristotle

00:15:54.630 --> 00:15:56.550
mentions it's rhetoric.

00:15:56.550 --> 00:15:58.694
This enthymeme gets you
to listen to a speaker

00:15:58.694 --> 00:16:00.860
or to get more tuned into
what the speaker's saying.

00:16:00.860 --> 00:16:02.490
I was thinking about a magazine.

00:16:02.490 --> 00:16:04.700
Endless pages, you're
flipping, you're

00:16:04.700 --> 00:16:06.400
seeing a lot of
stuff you expect,

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:09.790
articles, images, words
trying to sell things to you.

00:16:09.790 --> 00:16:12.000
And I remember a classic
ad I think they referred to

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.880
in the show is a Volkswagen
ad for, I think, the Beetle.

00:16:15.880 --> 00:16:20.440
It's a tiny little car
on this big white page.

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:22.160
The ad itself is very small.

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:23.430
It's a lot of wasted space.

00:16:23.430 --> 00:16:26.314
And I think the tagline
is, think small.

00:16:26.314 --> 00:16:27.730
Is that what you're
talking about?

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:28.235
JOSH WELTMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:16:28.235 --> 00:16:29.730
MALE SPEAKER: It confuses
you, catches your attention.

00:16:29.730 --> 00:16:32.310
JOSH WELTMAN: Imagine, we
talked about on the show.

00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:34.980
You're flipping through
this magazine circa 1961,

00:16:34.980 --> 00:16:38.030
and you come across this
big, empty white page

00:16:38.030 --> 00:16:39.130
with a little teeny car.

00:16:39.130 --> 00:16:41.930
And your head is
going, what is this?

00:16:41.930 --> 00:16:43.670
This is not-- this
should not be here.

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:45.300
This is confusing.

00:16:45.300 --> 00:16:46.730
What are they trying to say?

00:16:46.730 --> 00:16:48.500
Is this a mistake?

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:51.080
Where's the rest of the
stuff that goes on the page?

00:16:51.080 --> 00:16:53.420
Oh, think small.

00:16:53.420 --> 00:16:55.270
I get it.

00:16:55.270 --> 00:16:56.200
I'm engaged.

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:00.180
I see that they're
trying to say that it's

00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:06.650
about being different, or being
unexpected, or being unique,

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:08.349
or whatever that is.

00:17:08.349 --> 00:17:11.109
But for that
fraction of a second,

00:17:11.109 --> 00:17:17.810
when somebody's trying to
resolve that confusion,

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:23.170
you have an opportunity as a
seller of goods and services

00:17:23.170 --> 00:17:25.940
to engage them in a discussion.

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:29.464
They're open because they're
trying to figure something out.

00:17:29.464 --> 00:17:31.880
MALE SPEAKER: I think you
also-- last thing on this point.

00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:34.152
You mentioned adrenaline
and dopamine specifically

00:17:34.152 --> 00:17:35.360
get released in this process.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:36.401
JOSH WELTMAN: Yeah, sure.

00:17:36.401 --> 00:17:37.860
I mean, what your head is doing.

00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:40.400
I don't know, but I've read
articles like everybody else.

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:42.470
I'm not doctor, but--
when you're confused,

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:43.692
it's that fight or flight.

00:17:43.692 --> 00:17:45.400
You know, you're trying
to figure it out.

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:49.350
And then when the tumblers
fall in your mind,

00:17:49.350 --> 00:17:50.850
you feel that reward.

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:54.020
I've felt it trying
to come up with ideas.

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:56.760
I know when I've
solved the puzzle

00:17:56.760 --> 00:17:57.870
and what that feels like.

00:17:57.870 --> 00:18:00.130
And I think that
it's the combination

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:02.220
of chemicals that make you
feel that way going off

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:04.650
in your head.

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:07.930
That's the reason that an
enthymeme, literally translated

00:18:07.930 --> 00:18:10.630
from Greek, means "in
your mind," you know.

00:18:10.630 --> 00:18:12.990
It's happening in your head.

00:18:12.990 --> 00:18:15.310
MALE SPEAKER: Let's
