00:18:25.710 --> 00:18:27.460
I'd love to know-- I'm
sure a lot of folks

00:18:27.460 --> 00:18:30.190
here too as well-- how
were these pitches created

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:30.795
for the show?

00:18:30.795 --> 00:18:31.670
What was the process?

00:18:31.670 --> 00:18:33.459
Could you walk us through that?

00:18:33.459 --> 00:18:35.750
JOSH WELTMAN: One of the
things Matt Weiner-- if you're

00:18:35.750 --> 00:18:38.030
familiar with the show, Matt
Weiner is the showrunner.

00:18:38.030 --> 00:18:39.630
The person who
invented "Mad Men"

00:18:39.630 --> 00:18:42.780
is a stickler for accuracy.

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:48.010
And early on we were friends--
or we're still friends,

00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:50.839
but we were just friends before
he had a show on television.

00:18:50.839 --> 00:18:52.380
And he was talking
about advertising,

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:58.590
and we said, to be accurate
about creating ads,

00:18:58.590 --> 00:19:03.240
ads are created in the agency
environment, at that time

00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:05.090
a team of an art
director working

00:19:05.090 --> 00:19:06.810
with a writer, the
pictures and the words

00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:09.550
working together to come
up with a concept the way I

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:11.310
was just describing.

00:19:11.310 --> 00:19:14.830
Typically, shows based
in the advertising world,

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:17.060
or movies based in
the advertising world,

00:19:17.060 --> 00:19:20.580
before "Mad Men," a writer
would write the script

00:19:20.580 --> 00:19:22.920
and they'd march the script
down to the art department,

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.670
and the art department
would make up the ad the way

00:19:25.670 --> 00:19:27.490
they make up any other prop.

00:19:27.490 --> 00:19:29.510
And that's how you
got advertising.

00:19:29.510 --> 00:19:33.610
And Matt recognized
that we would probably

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:38.600
get more accurate ads if the
writer's room began working

00:19:38.600 --> 00:19:39.990
the way real agencies did.

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:41.820
And I'm an art
director by background,

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:43.360
and he brought me
in one day a week

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:45.800
to work on the business
stories and the concept

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:48.530
for ads with the writers
as they happened.

00:19:48.530 --> 00:19:49.332
And that's how--

00:19:49.332 --> 00:19:51.290
MALE SPEAKER: Could you
walk us through, maybe,

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:53.310
how "The Carousel" came about?

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:56.070
JOSH WELTMAN: At
the end of Season 1,

00:19:56.070 --> 00:19:57.690
the main character,
Don Draper, has

00:19:57.690 --> 00:20:00.230
had-- his marriage
is breaking up,

00:20:00.230 --> 00:20:02.640
his business is falling
apart, his brother

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:06.240
has just committed suicide.

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:10.650
And Matt said, we need a
business story or a product

00:20:10.650 --> 00:20:14.250
that explains, lets
the audience see

00:20:14.250 --> 00:20:16.040
what Don is feeling
about his marriage,

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:18.330
his business, his
brother's suicide.

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:23.459
And that's sort of
a tough-- I'm not

00:20:23.459 --> 00:20:25.250
sure there are a lot
of products like that.

00:20:25.250 --> 00:20:26.960
But one of the
things that I used

00:20:26.960 --> 00:20:29.814
to do before going
into the writer's room

00:20:29.814 --> 00:20:31.230
to work with the
writers and stuff

00:20:31.230 --> 00:20:38.460
is, I would leaf through the
PDFs of "The New York Times"

00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:42.572
advertising section of the
week that the story on the show

00:20:42.572 --> 00:20:43.280
was taking place.

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:47.660
And so I'd go-- it
was October of 1961.

00:20:47.660 --> 00:20:50.760
I'd read the advertising
column in "The New York Times."

00:20:50.760 --> 00:20:57.250
And I noticed that Kodak was
working on a slide projector,

00:20:57.250 --> 00:20:59.830
or there was something,
and I checked and saw

00:20:59.830 --> 00:21:01.170
that it came out the next year.

00:21:01.170 --> 00:21:02.580
It was called the carousel.

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:06.600
I figured whatever they were
doing at the time in real life

00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:08.310
was probably happening
about that time,

00:21:08.310 --> 00:21:10.330
with a year kind of thing.

00:21:10.330 --> 00:21:19.350
And I remember my father--
in the '60s, cameras and film

00:21:19.350 --> 00:21:21.890
and Super 8 cameras
and hi-fi equipment.

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:24.900
They were the high tech
gadgets of their time.

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:29.670
And these guys like Don
Draper spent a lot of time

00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:36.020
with photographic equipment,
single lens reflex cameras,

00:21:36.020 --> 00:21:37.460
all that sort of thing.

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:40.330
And I thought maybe he
did what my dad did,

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:43.730
which is have a bunch of
slides of trips in the closet,

00:21:43.730 --> 00:21:44.670
and sort through them.

00:21:44.670 --> 00:21:48.070
And if we could use
some of his slides

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:52.630
from his life in
a pitch, we could

00:21:52.630 --> 00:21:56.460
understand what he was
feeling about his business,

00:21:56.460 --> 00:21:59.440
his marriage, his
life in general.

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:00.980
And so that's what
we brought in.

00:22:00.980 --> 00:22:03.030
We probably could have
done the same thing

00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:06.660
if the product had been a Super
8 movie camera or something

00:22:06.660 --> 00:22:08.950
like that, anything
where he could've

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:13.240
used his own images in the
sales pitch to the client.

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:16.227
But the slide projector
worked really well.

00:22:16.227 --> 00:22:18.310
MALE SPEAKER: So one of
the tag lines for the show

00:22:18.310 --> 00:22:20.020
is "Where the truth lies."

00:22:20.020 --> 00:22:23.300
And you write that the main
insight into Don's character,

00:22:23.300 --> 00:22:25.960
and the most important
conceit of the show,

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:30.350
is that Don Draper can lie
anywhere except in advertising.

00:22:30.350 --> 00:22:31.860
And why is that?

00:22:31.860 --> 00:22:34.810
JOSH WELTMAN: He's lying to his
wife, he's lying to his kids,

00:22:34.810 --> 00:22:36.960
he's lying to his partner--
he lies to everybody,

00:22:36.960 --> 00:22:38.490
he lies to himself.

00:22:38.490 --> 00:22:41.710
But it was very
important to Matt Weiner

00:22:41.710 --> 00:22:47.830
that Don, as the main
character, be good at his job.

00:22:47.830 --> 00:22:50.570
He thought that
the audience needed

00:22:50.570 --> 00:22:53.370
him to be good at
something, to respect him

00:22:53.370 --> 00:22:56.677
on some level, or else all this
other stuff that he was doing,

00:22:56.677 --> 00:22:58.010
that no one would stick with it.

00:22:58.010 --> 00:22:59.550
It was just too dark.

00:22:59.550 --> 00:23:04.710
And so I felt that
what we were looking at

00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:07.620
was a guy who
could lie anywhere,

00:23:07.620 --> 00:23:08.980
except in the advertising.

00:23:08.980 --> 00:23:15.440
In the advertising, he's basing
his work on truthful insights

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:17.990
that he has into people.

00:23:17.990 --> 00:23:23.040
He obviously understands what
makes people tick very well,

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:26.060
or he couldn't write good ads.

00:23:26.060 --> 00:23:29.950
And that makes his own
kind of internal struggle

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:34.700
to understand what's motivating
him, and what makes him tick,

00:23:34.700 --> 00:23:37.160
even more poignant.

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:39.880
MALE SPEAKER: So I wonder, are
there Don Drapers out there?

00:23:39.880 --> 00:23:41.790
Were there, are
there people who just

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:44.592
walk into a pitch
like that and just--

00:23:44.592 --> 00:23:45.550
JOSH WELTMAN: And kill?

00:23:45.550 --> 00:23:47.190
Yeah, sure.

00:23:47.190 --> 00:23:51.410
Not as often and
consistently as a guy

00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:54.190
who's working in
