worked and created,

00:24:47.720 --> 00:24:52.430
like, Frankenstein,
the ultimate ad guy,

00:24:52.430 --> 00:24:54.860
bits and pieces from everywhere.

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:56.780
MALE SPEAKER: So one
of my favorite comments

00:24:56.780 --> 00:24:59.470
about the show-- I think it was
the week of the last episode--

00:24:59.470 --> 00:25:01.420
so Matt Weiner was
being interviewed,

00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:08.860
and he said that the show "Mad
Men" is about what people want,

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:12.190
what they can get, and how
happiness lies somewhere

00:25:12.190 --> 00:25:12.770
in between.

00:25:12.770 --> 00:25:15.600
And it reminded me of what you
talked about happiness being,

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:17.560
as this different
expectation reality.

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:18.840
Could you talk about that
in relation to the show?

00:25:18.840 --> 00:25:21.298
JOSH WELTMAN: Yeah, I think
that's what the story is about.

00:25:21.298 --> 00:25:24.630
I think it's about trying to
bridge that gap between a man's

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:27.050
expectations and his reality.

00:25:27.050 --> 00:25:31.300
And every story is
the story of how

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:34.710
someone got something,
or didn't get something

00:25:34.710 --> 00:25:36.272
that they desired.

00:25:36.272 --> 00:25:37.980
And that's what we're
watching, or that's

00:25:37.980 --> 00:25:40.650
what we watched, over the course
of eight seasons of "Mad Men."

00:25:40.650 --> 00:25:45.040
How does he get the
life he thinks he wants?

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:48.560
Or how does he get what
makes him feel happy?

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:50.560
MALE SPEAKER: Well, I've
got questions for days,

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:52.351
but I'd love to take
some from the audience

00:25:52.351 --> 00:25:54.180
if you guys are curious at all.

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:55.729
There's Mike, right
in the middle.

00:25:55.729 --> 00:25:56.520
MIKE: I'll ask one.

00:25:56.520 --> 00:26:00.810
So my question is, would you
see advertising in utopia?

00:26:00.810 --> 00:26:05.760
And so going back to that
expectation around advertising,

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:09.000
could we see the explosion
of ways of advertising

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:13.052
as a barometer for getting
farther from utopia?

00:26:13.052 --> 00:26:13.760
JOSH WELTMAN: OK.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:16.870
Would there be
advertising in utopia?

00:26:16.870 --> 00:26:19.042
You mean, where everybody's
happy, do we need--

00:26:19.042 --> 00:26:20.250
MIKE: There's no expectation.

00:26:20.250 --> 00:26:24.240
JOSH WELTMAN: There's no
expect-- I don't know.

00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:25.282
It's a tough one.

00:26:25.282 --> 00:26:26.740
I was thinking
about that, kind of,

00:26:26.740 --> 00:26:29.730
when I saw
"Tomorrowland" come out,

00:26:29.730 --> 00:26:34.660
because I think that what's
missing a lot from people's

00:26:34.660 --> 00:26:41.730
lives today are basically
somebody's vision of where

00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:43.710
we should be heading.

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:50.140
It sounds cute that, when you
think of Walt Disney building

00:26:50.140 --> 00:26:52.140
Tomorrowland, and
when I was little,

00:26:52.140 --> 00:26:54.490
how you'd go to the
Monsanto exhibit

00:26:54.490 --> 00:26:57.600
of the kitchen of tomorrow
and all that sort of stuff.

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:01.070
And it was kind of
funky, but it made

00:27:01.070 --> 00:27:03.490
you feel good that we
were heading somewhere,

00:27:03.490 --> 00:27:07.510
you know, that those
expectations were--

00:27:07.510 --> 00:27:10.980
they may be right, they may be
wrong, they may be whatever.

00:27:10.980 --> 00:27:12.810
But they were shared
by so many people.

00:27:12.810 --> 00:27:14.980
And we had this
idea that we were

00:27:14.980 --> 00:27:18.430
all kind of heading
towards this one direction.

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:23.120
And I think that people's
vision of the future,

00:27:23.120 --> 00:27:25.475
and their expectation
is so fragmented,

00:27:25.475 --> 00:27:28.120
it doesn't feel like
there's any one person

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:32.350
or group of visionary
thinkers who are saying,

00:27:32.350 --> 00:27:37.410
yeah, maybe let's get together
for the World's Fair of 2018

00:27:37.410 --> 00:27:40.610
and lay out where we're going.

00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:42.930
So I don't know if that
answers the question or not.

00:27:42.930 --> 00:27:45.520
But yeah, I think you
really do need expectations.

00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:51.770
And I think the angst going
on today, or part of it,

00:27:51.770 --> 00:27:54.840
is that people don't
know where we're heading.

00:27:54.840 --> 00:27:57.300
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so when
you talk about Don Draper

00:27:57.300 --> 00:28:01.510
as a profile of an ideal
"Mad Men" in his time, two

00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:02.880
questions.

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:04.950
How did you put
yourself in that era?

00:28:04.950 --> 00:28:06.510
Was there much of an adjustment?

00:28:06.510 --> 00:28:10.160
And secondly, what is
the profile of today,

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:11.810
and how might be different?

00:28:11.810 --> 00:28:15.951
Do we value different things
than a successful advertising

00:28:15.951 --> 00:28:16.450
person?

00:28:16.450 --> 00:28:17.930
JOSH WELTMAN: In a persuader?

00:28:17.930 --> 00:28:20.300
I don't even think we
call them successful

00:28:20.300 --> 00:28:22.140
advertising people anymore.

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:30.270
You know, because
advertising is sort of

00:28:30.270 --> 00:28:34.290
in such a state of
transition and flux,

00:28:34.290 --> 00:28:38.970
it's hard to think of what
makes advertising successful

00:28:38.970 --> 00:28:39.670
nowadays.

00:28:39.670 --> 00:28:41.470
And it's hard to
think of someone

00:28:41.470 --> 00:28:43.430
who feels successful doing it.

00:28:43.430 --> 00:28:48.010
I had a friend say, maybe six
months ago-- a seasoned ad

00:28:48.010 --> 00:28:55.500
person, a very good writer
and good at his job--

00:28:55.500 --> 00:29:00.240
and he was talking and
lamenting the place

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:03.550
that he worked spends a
lot of time sort of talking

00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:06.590
about creating
experiences rather

00:29:06.590 --> 00:29:09.010
than tools of persuasion.

00:29:09.010 --> 00:29:13.290
And he said, we used to
make tools for clients,

00:29:13.290 --> 00:29:15.350
and now we make toys.

00:29:15.350 --> 00:29:18.820
We used to really
think about what

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:22.890
the messages that
we were making,

00:29:22.890 --> 00:29:24.460
what they were
supposed to do, what

00:29:24.460 --> 00:29:25.970
the payoff was supposed to be.

00:29:25.970 --> 00:29:28.210
I talk a lot about
that in the book,

00:29:28.210 --> 00:29:31.850
because with each of those
four different types of ads,

00:29:31.850 --> 00:29:33.750
there's a different
metric involved.

00:29:33.750 --> 00:29:36.690
And you knew what you
were trying to do,

00:29:36.690 --> 00:29:39.290
and you knew if you
were making progress.

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:46.760
Yeah that one, I
really didn't think

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:53.690
things had changed a lot between
when I was working even 2010.

00:29:53.690 --> 00:29:58.190
And I'll tell you the big moment
that was really different.

00:29:58.190 --> 00:30:02.930
I remember in 1989, when the
big advertising conglomerate

00:30:02.930 --> 00:30:05.500
that I was working for
sent out a memo that

00:30:05.500 --> 00:30:09.850
said they were no longer going
to expense liquor at lunch.

00:30:12.500 --> 00:30:15.390
And one of the old
copywriters, really

00:30:15.390 --> 00:30:18.830
genius guy who'd been doing
it for a long, long time,

00:30:18.830 --> 00:30:20.740
came and sat down in my office.

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:23.860
And I was the young
20-something guy,

00:30:23.860 --> 00:30:26.520
and he was-- really
had been doing it

00:30:26.520 --> 00:30:31.000
since like the '40s or '50s
at least, but just a genius.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:32.670
And he says, that's it.

00:30:32.670 --> 00:30:33.630
That's the end of this.

00:30:36.249 --> 00:30:37.790
I'll tell you how
he meant it, but he

00:30:37.790 --> 00:30:46.880
said, what kind of person
would approve this stuff sober,

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:48.690
you know?

00:30:48.690 --> 00:30:51.400
And he didn't mean that the
account guys were getting

00:30:51.400 --> 00:30:55.730
the clients drunk at lunch
to try and pull something

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:57.100
over on them.

00:30:57.100 --> 00:30:58.910
But he was trying to
say, look, when you're

00:30:58.910 --> 00:31:03.390
trying to do something edgy
or exciting or engaging,

00:31:03.390 --> 00:31:08.480
or something that
can't be rationalized

00:31:08.480 --> 00:31:11.530
in a cost-benefit
type of way, you've

00:31:11.530 --> 00:31:14.030
got to make these
guys brave, you know?

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:15.810
And that's what the liquor did.

00:31:15.810 --> 00:31:20.450
And after that, people
were much more tentative,

00:31:20.450 --> 00:31:27.430
and sort of-- I never I heard
the phrase "risk averse"

00:31:27.430 --> 00:31:30.305
until they said they weren't
going to expense liquor

00:31:30.305 --> 00:31:31.940
at lunch.

00:31:31.940 --> 00:31:33.920
I'll just put it that way.

00:31:33.920 --> 00:31:34.580
Yeah.

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:35.050
JOHN: How you doing?

00:31:35.050 --> 00:31:35.591
I'm John.

00:31:35.591 --> 00:31:37.090
I'm from the YouTube
marketing team.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:39.780
And I gotta say, "Mad Men" is
as much a case study for us,

00:31:39.780 --> 00:31:42.250
in some respects, as it
is like an episodic thing.

00:31:42.250 --> 00:31:47.110
We talk about it a lot at work,
and a lot of fans at YouTube

00:31:47.110 --> 00:31:48.910
and I know Google wide.

00:31:48.910 --> 00:31:51.670
My question was, I was
hoping you could help me

00:31:51.670 --> 00:31:53.860
kind of sort through a
moral dilemma I sometimes

00:31:53.860 --> 00:31:55.850
think about when it
comes to marketing.

00:31:55.850 --> 00:31:57.750
And I talk about
this with friends

00:31:57.750 --> 00:32:00.530
who are on the agency side
and go through this as well.

00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:03.820
And I wonder, what do
you think about how

00:32:03.820 --> 00:32:05.660
advertising and
the need for it had

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:08.730
led to materialism and
consumerism in the world today?

00:32:08.730 --> 00:32:11.580
Like I feel like a lot
of us tend to buy things

00:32:11.580 --> 00:32:12.850
that maybe we don't need.

00:32:12.850 --> 00:32:16.180
And being in marketing and
having friends in advertising,

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:18.390
sometimes we think about,
are we pushing messages

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:19.500
that we don't believe in?

00:32:19.500 --> 00:32:22.040
Are we selling products that
maybe people don't need?

00:32:22.040 --> 00:32:23.080
And--

00:32:23.080 --> 00:32:24.320
JOSH WELTMAN: No, I
know what you're asking.

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:25.080
MALE SPEAKER: You should
tell the Taco Bell story

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:26.413
while you're trying to say that.

00:32:26.413 --> 00:32:29.830
JOSH WELTMAN: No, the first day
that I went into the writers'

00:32:29.830 --> 00:32:33.439
room on "Mad Men,"
I remember I brought

00:32:33.439 --> 00:32:34.480
in three pieces of paper.

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:36.420
They're now hanging
in the Museum

00:32:36.420 --> 00:32:39.960
of Moving Images in New York
with the set-- or not the set,

00:32:39.960 --> 00:32:42.280
the whole writers' room has
moved there-- but on one

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:46.500
of them it said, "Scary.

00:32:46.500 --> 00:32:54.590
There are big corporations out
there that are-- what was it?

00:32:54.590 --> 00:32:55.300
It's scary.

00:32:55.300 --> 00:32:57.060
There are big
corporations out there

00:32:57.060 --> 00:33:02.890
who are controlling what
you think and what you feel

00:33:02.890 --> 00:33:07.390
and making you buy things
that leave you broke

00:33:07.390 --> 00:33:08.930
and feeling empty.

00:33:08.930 --> 00:33:11.760
And then it said, scarier.

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:13.550
There are no big
corporations out

00:33:13.550 --> 00:33:16.310
there controlling
what you think, feel,

00:33:16.310 --> 00:33:19.360
and making you buy things
that leave you broke

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:22.500
and feeling empty, that
it's kind of in your head.

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:29.320
I think that people
believe that they can make

00:33:29.320 --> 00:33:31.850
their life better, you know.

00:33:31.850 --> 00:33:33.510
I don't think I put
that belief there.

00:33:33.510 --> 00:33:35.640
I don't think you put
that belief there.

00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:38.030
I think that's the
human condition, that we

00:33:38.030 --> 00:33:41.570
believe things can be better.

00:33:41.570 --> 00:33:45.430
I think that the problem
is that we think things

00:33:45.430 --> 00:33:49.770
that we buy-- we think
that better can be bought.

00:33:49.770 --> 00:33:51.260
And usually, it can't be.

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:54.140
You gotta sort of
look at who you are

00:33:54.140 --> 00:33:56.140
and what you're asking
for and those sort

00:33:56.140 --> 00:33:58.080
of things kind of thing.

00:33:58.080 --> 00:34:01.470
So I don't think that the
desire to make your life better

00:34:01.470 --> 00:34:05.400
is something that's instilled--
that's caused consumerism.

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:08.820
I think that what causes
consumerism is thinking

00:34:08.820 --> 00:34:13.659
that stuff that you can consume
will make you feel better

00:34:13.659 --> 00:34:14.870
about life.

00:34:14.870 --> 00:34:21.832
And that's not what-- the
advertisers aren't planting

00:34:21.832 --> 00:34:22.790
that thought in people.

00:34:22.790 --> 00:34:26.429
There's a lot of reasons that
I think that that exists.

00:34:26.429 --> 00:34:31.750
And it's about people finding
what truly makes them happy,

00:34:31.750 --> 00:34:37.070
and not the stuff
that's being advertised,

00:34:37.070 --> 00:34:38.380
or how it will make them happy.

00:34:38.380 --> 00:34:39.690
JOHN: I'm just curious
as, like, a follow up.

00:34:39.690 --> 00:34:41.340
Do you why, or do
you have a thought

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:45.290
as to why consumerism is higher
today than it was before?

00:34:45.290 --> 00:34:47.370
JOSH WELTMAN: I mean,
consumerism of some things

00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:49.380
are-- what specifically?

00:34:49.380 --> 00:34:53.530
Because I don't know-- I think
there's more people with-- you

00:34:53.530 --> 00:34:57.170
know, like when I
was coming up, China

00:34:57.170 --> 00:35:03.090
was not consuming the same sort
of things that they are now.

00:35:03.090 --> 00:35:05.550
But I know the stuff
that they were consuming

00:35:05.550 --> 00:35:07.700
wasn't making them
particularly happy.

00:35:07.700 --> 00:35:11.310
They wanted to
have what you have.

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:14.910
They wanted cars and
city life and choices,

00:35:14.910 --> 00:35:18.480
and the supermarket
and stuff like that.

00:35:18.480 --> 00:35:21.000
So they think they're
consuming stuff

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:22.201
for the same reason you do.

00:35:22.201 --> 00:35:23.950
They think this stuff
will make you happy.

00:35:23.950 --> 00:35:26.990
Maybe it will,
maybe-- I don't know.

00:35:26.990 --> 00:35:30.850
The more dissatisfied
with the stuff

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:36.304
we got, we try and improve it
and get new stuff, I think.

00:35:36.304 --> 00:35:36.970
JOHN: Thank you.

00:35:36.970 --> 00:35:39.160
JOSH WELTMAN: Sure.

00:35:39.160 --> 00:35:42.160
AUDIENCE: So storytelling
is very in vogue today

00:35:42.160 --> 00:35:44.370
in business and speaking.

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:47.610
Can you take us to where your
vision is on storytelling

00:35:47.610 --> 00:35:48.470
the next 10 years?

00:35:48.470 --> 00:35:49.845
What should we be
thinking about?

00:35:49.845 --> 00:35:52.450
Or is it really the same
from Don Draper's time today

00:35:52.450 --> 00:35:53.870
and tomorrow?

00:35:53.870 --> 00:35:56.670
JOSH WELTMAN: I think that
a lot of the difference

00:35:56.670 --> 00:36:00.100
between the industrial economy
and the knowledge economy

00:36:00.100 --> 00:36:04.450
is that in the industrial
economy, managers that

00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:08.760
could manage things that could
be measured, like time, space,

00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:12.890
and energy, were
really the ones that

00:36:12.890 --> 00:36:19.830
made a huge difference
in the price of goods

00:36:19.830 --> 00:36:22.200
and the profitability
of companies.

00:36:22.200 --> 00:36:25.450
Then in the information
economy, there's

00:36:25.450 --> 00:36:27.600
sort of good services
and ideas that can't

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:29.290
be quantified or measured.

00:36:29.290 --> 00:36:36.610
And those things are sort of--
since they can't be measured,

00:36:36.610 --> 00:36:41.870
they're really more
about-- how do I say this?

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:43.790
They're really
more about stories

00:36:43.790 --> 00:36:47.610
and the emotional connections
between those things.

00:36:47.610 --> 00:36:52.090
So I think the more our economy
becomes more based on goods,

00:36:52.090 --> 00:36:57.290
services, and ideas, things that
can't be quantified, measured,

00:36:57.290 --> 00:36:59.690
or really managed
in the same way

00:36:59.690 --> 00:37:02.530
that measurable
things are managed,

00:37:02.530 --> 00:37:04.925
storytelling becomes
more important.

00:37:04.925 --> 00:37:05.800
Does that make sense?

00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:06.590
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:06.590 --> 00:37:07.130
Thank you.

00:37:07.130 --> 00:37:08.969
MALE SPEAKER: Just two
more questions here.

00:37:08.969 --> 00:37:09.510
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:09.510 --> 00:37:12.230
I wanted to get
your opinion on what

00:37:12.230 --> 00:37:15.290
you think the story behind
"Mad Men" really means.

00:37:15.290 --> 00:37:17.520
Like what is the main
message that the show is

00:37:17.520 --> 00:37:20.270
trying to convey to the audience
through the journey of Don

00:37:20.270 --> 00:37:20.770
Draper?

00:37:20.770 --> 00:37:22.020
MALE SPEAKER: How does it end?

00:37:23.686 --> 00:37:27.340
JOSH WELTMAN: You know, I
couldn't possibly answer that.

00:37:27.340 --> 00:37:33.640
It's so different being
inside the eye of the storm

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:36.630
and working to put it together.

00:37:36.630 --> 00:37:41.050
And I think it's really best if
people like me who are in there

00:37:41.050 --> 00:37:46.090
leave it up to other people
to get what they get.

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:49.812
Sometimes I got what
Matt got, and sometimes I

00:37:49.812 --> 00:37:51.520
didn't get what the
writers got, or I got

00:37:51.520 --> 00:37:52.590
something completely different.

00:37:52.590 --> 00:37:53.730
I mean, I'm just like you.

00:37:53.730 --> 00:37:58.720
When I see it on TV, it's
like, oh my god, you know?

00:37:58.720 --> 00:38:01.390
It sure doesn't feel
when it's put together,

00:38:01.390 --> 00:38:04.290
and you're looking at
it, like it did when

00:38:04.290 --> 00:38:07.430
you were trying to make it.

00:38:07.430 --> 00:38:07.982
I don't know.

00:38:07.982 --> 00:38:10.190
AUDIENCE: Perhaps a different
way to ask the question

00:38:10.190 --> 00:38:12.490
is, what has his journey
meant for you personally

00:38:12.490 --> 00:38:14.114
over the time that
you've worked on it?

00:38:14.114 --> 00:38:18.800
JOSH WELTMAN: Oh, it's been just
