00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:37.940
That's great, thanks.

00:38:37.940 --> 00:38:38.580
MALE SPEAKER: Last
question for you, Josh.

00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:39.660
We're at a tech company.

00:38:39.660 --> 00:38:41.900
And you talk about tech
companies in the book.

00:38:41.900 --> 00:38:46.290
You say that they fall prey to
throwing things over the wall.

00:38:46.290 --> 00:38:49.227
And you actually mention
Google, which I love.

00:38:49.227 --> 00:38:50.060
JOSH WELTMAN: Sorry.

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:51.620
MALE SPEAKER: No, it's great.

00:38:51.620 --> 00:38:55.160
You actually mention the first
product I worked on here.

00:38:55.160 --> 00:38:57.960
What do tech companies do when
they throw it over the wall?

00:38:57.960 --> 00:38:58.860
What does that mean?

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:01.235
JOSH WELTMAN: The first time
I heard the phrase "throw it

00:39:01.235 --> 00:39:04.060
over the wall" was when I was
Creative Director on Microsoft.

00:39:04.060 --> 00:39:08.180
And what that meant
was bringing a product

00:39:08.180 --> 00:39:13.650
to market because you
can, without necessarily

00:39:13.650 --> 00:39:20.830
thinking about why or how you're
going to get people to buy it.

00:39:20.830 --> 00:39:25.400
It's making it--
I'm sorry, bringing

00:39:25.400 --> 00:39:27.330
it to market because
you can make it,

00:39:27.330 --> 00:39:29.790
rather than bringing it to
market because you think

00:39:29.790 --> 00:39:32.190
you can make people buy it.

00:39:32.190 --> 00:39:38.140
So without considering that,
sometimes things fall flat.

00:39:38.140 --> 00:39:39.420
It doesn't really--

00:39:39.420 --> 00:39:41.794
MALE SPEAKER: How does a tech
company make people buy it?

00:39:41.794 --> 00:39:43.149
How do you create that itch?

00:39:43.149 --> 00:39:44.940
JOSH WELTMAN: I think
a high tech company--

00:39:44.940 --> 00:39:47.890
I think the hardest thing, or
the most important thing to do,

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:57.720
is to keep control of the
metaphor, the metaphor being

00:39:57.720 --> 00:40:02.770
sort of what it's like,
what the product is

00:40:02.770 --> 00:40:04.640
like in the real world.

00:40:04.640 --> 00:40:09.630
You know, IBM spent
a lot of money 10,

00:40:09.630 --> 00:40:14.290
15 years ago
advertising e-Business.

00:40:14.290 --> 00:40:15.920
e-Business was the metaphor.

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:20.640
It was the idea of
business done online.

00:40:20.640 --> 00:40:23.450
None of the machines or the
software that allowed business

00:40:23.450 --> 00:40:26.770
to be done online
really existed.

00:40:26.770 --> 00:40:29.800
So the money was
spent so that IBM

00:40:29.800 --> 00:40:33.760
would be the company that
controlled what it meant

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:39.060
to do business online
by showing people

00:40:39.060 --> 00:40:43.830
a story, a fiction of
what it looked like when

00:40:43.830 --> 00:40:47.760
so and so in Poland could
create a cheese shop

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:51.820
and post i6 and get an order
from someone in-- before any

00:40:51.820 --> 00:40:53.470
of this could actually happen.

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:56.030
You had to create
that Tomorrowland,

00:40:56.030 --> 00:40:58.550
that vision of the future,
that that's where we're going.

00:40:58.550 --> 00:41:01.679
MALE SPEAKER: Did Google
ever do this, do you think?

00:41:01.679 --> 00:41:02.470
JOSH WELTMAN: Yeah.

00:41:02.470 --> 00:41:05.465
I think Google did it.

00:41:05.465 --> 00:41:07.340
I was telling you the
story of the first time

00:41:07.340 --> 00:41:09.990
I heard that-- Google did it
when they came up with the name

00:41:09.990 --> 00:41:14.180
Google, because I can
remember like it was yesterday

00:41:14.180 --> 00:41:18.620
the first time I heard
somebody say, in an agency,

00:41:18.620 --> 00:41:19.780
go Google that.

00:41:19.780 --> 00:41:22.320
I didn't know what they meant.

00:41:22.320 --> 00:41:24.682
I thought they could have
been telling me go fuck myself

00:41:24.682 --> 00:41:25.640
or something like that.

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:28.120
I mean, what do you
mean, go Google it?

00:41:28.120 --> 00:41:30.170
And when they said,
you know, there's

00:41:30.170 --> 00:41:35.730
this thing on the Internet
that'll answer any question,

00:41:35.730 --> 00:41:39.190
it made me very curious to
find out more about that,

00:41:39.190 --> 00:41:41.980
because suddenly there was
someone in the office who

00:41:41.980 --> 00:41:43.450
had a tool that I didn't have.

00:41:43.450 --> 00:41:44.477
They had an edge.

00:41:44.477 --> 00:41:46.060
They had all the
answers in the world.

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:47.185
MALE SPEAKER: An enthymeme.

00:41:47.185 --> 00:41:48.400
JOSH WELTMAN: Yeah.

00:41:48.400 --> 00:41:51.400
And I had to go
and check that out.

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:58.450
And it was having a word
for a product and a service

00:41:58.450 --> 00:42:00.820
that had never existed before.

00:42:00.820 --> 00:42:04.890
And calling it something that
I'd never heard before that

00:42:04.890 --> 00:42:07.060
made me absolutely have
to scratch that itch.

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:09.160
I couldn't allow there
to be another person

00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:12.140
in the agency who knew
about this valuable thing,

00:42:12.140 --> 00:42:14.270
or wonderful thing that
I didn't know about.

00:42:14.270 --> 00:42:14.770
So yeah.

00:42:14.770 --> 00:42:16.010
MALE SPEAKER: And you
scratched a couple times a day,

00:42:16.010 --> 00:42:16.510
I take it.

